<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-568-448  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 568 448.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  June 18 1990 v7 n24 p18(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Cahners-Ziff Publishing Associates LP 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>TransLaser converts printers' languages to Adobe PostScript.andO;(Camintonn Corp.) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ballou, Melinda-Carol.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Cammintonn Inc announces TransLaser, a printer-independentperipheral that converts printer languages to Adobe PostScript.andO;The Translaser accepts data in the print queue, generates theproper equivalent in the Adobe PostScript page descriptionlanguage and signals the target printer.andP;  The peripheral canaccept incoming data during printing and respond to two differentcomputer inputs.andP;  TransLaser gives users the benefit of aPostScript printer without requiring the use of differentsoftware.andP;  TransLaser also enables users to print ASCII text.andP;  Theperipheral, which includes emulations for a variety of vendors'computers, costs $1,295.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Camintonn Corp. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Camintonn TransLaser (Computer peripheral) (product introduction)PostScript (Printer software) (equipment and supplies).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionPeripheralsConversionProgramming Languages.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>TransLaser converts printers' languages to Adobe PostScriptandM;IRVINE, Calif.andP;  -- Camintonn has begun shipping the TransLaser, aprinter-independent peripheral that converts printer languages to AdobePostScript.andM;Before beginning a print job, the user issues a command telling theTransLaser which printer type it will be emulating.andP;  The TransLaswer thenaccepts the data to be printed, generates the proper equivalent in the AdobePostScript page description language and communicates is to the targetprinter, company officials said.andM;The TransLaser can accept incoming data during printing and can respond totwo separate computer inputs, according to the officials.andM;&quot;Historically, every printer manufacturer has had a different language sothat users were basically committed to the company they started with,&quot; saidDrew Wilkins, Camintonn's marketing manager.andP;  &quot;PostScript is the firstprinter language that different manufacturers [supported], and with text andgraphics, it has brought a lot of benefits to users.andP;  The problem is, it lefta lot of hardware and software products out of touch because they had theirown proprietary [printer] languages.&quot;andM;No different software neededandM;Wilkins said 80 percent of DEC software applications don't supportPostScript, but that Camintonn's TransLaser gives users the benefits ofPostScript printers without requiring them to use different software.andM;&quot;Our box sits between the host and the printer.andP;  You tell it which [printer]you want to print to, and it will take the data and send it to the PostScriptprinter without host overhead,&quot; he said.andM;Emulations are included for DEC's LN03, LN03+, LN03R ScriptPrinter,Hewlett-Packard's LaserJet Series II, HP 7475A plotter, Tektronix's 4010/4014and the Xerox Diablo 630 ECS.andM;According to Wilkins, many multiemulation laser printers require a pause ofone or two seconds, or a reset of the printer, wich can stop or stall a queueand lose data.andP;  These problems don't exist with TransLaser, he said.andM;The product also enables users to print ASCII text.andM;The TransLaser is priced at $1,295.andO;</TEXT></DOC>